</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Cardiac amyloidosis (CA) has long been recognized as a rare disease. However, recent advances in cardiac imaging have led to increased identification of hidden CA in patients diagnosed with heart failure. This shift suggests that the actual incidence of CA is underestimated. The prognosis of CA is generally poor, especially in patients with advanced heart failure. However, recent developments in therapeutic interventions have improved the survival of patients with CA. An early diagnosis and interventions involving effective therapies are essential contributors to improved prognoses. Recent noninvasive diagnostic imaging modalities such as echocardiography, cardiac MRI, and nuclear imaging have facilitated the precise and early diagnosis of CA and enabled the initiation of appropriate management. The authors present an updated review of the clinical features of CA, including a discussion of current trends in noninvasive diagnostic imaging.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2020</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020190069">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020190069">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic" aria-label="Drawings illustrate the differences between a normal heart and a heart with CA. CA is characterized by the accumulation of amyloid fibrils (black regions in right drawing) in the myocardial interstitium and increases in the thickness and mass of the ventricular wall, resulting in progressive diastolic and systolic dysfunction."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig1.jpeg" height="1277" width="2990" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Drawings illustrate the differences between a normal heart and a heart with CA. CA is characterized by the accumulation of amyloid fibrils (black regions in right drawing) in the myocardial interstitium and increases in the thickness and mass of the ventricular wall, resulting in progressive diastolic and systolic dysfunction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic" aria-label="Photomicrographs from endomyocardial biopsy in a patient with CA. (a) Hematoxylin-eosin–stained section (original magnification, ×200) reveals deposition of nonstructural substances (light pink) in the myocardial interstitium. (b) Congo red–stained section (original magnification, ×200) shows a deep pink to red coloration."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig2a.jpeg" height="1106" width="1473" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Photomicrographs from endomyocardial biopsy in a patient with CA. <b>(a)</b> Hematoxylin-eosin–stained section (original magnification, ×200) reveals deposition of nonstructural substances (light pink) in the myocardial interstitium. <b>(b)</b> Congo red–stained section (original magnification, ×200) shows a deep pink to red coloration.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic" aria-label="Photomicrographs from endomyocardial biopsy in a patient with CA. (a) Hematoxylin-eosin–stained section (original magnification, ×200) reveals deposition of nonstructural substances (light pink) in the myocardial interstitium. (b) Congo red–stained section (original magnification, ×200) shows a deep pink to red coloration."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig2b.jpeg" height="1106" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Photomicrographs from endomyocardial biopsy in a patient with CA. <b>(a)</b> Hematoxylin-eosin–stained section (original magnification, ×200) reveals deposition of nonstructural substances (light pink) in the myocardial interstitium. <b>(b)</b> Congo red–stained section (original magnification, ×200) shows a deep pink to red coloration.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic" aria-label="Proposed diagnostic algorithm for patients with CA. CMR = cardiac MRI, ECV = extracellular volume, H:CL = heart-to–contralateral chest ratio, LGE = late gadolinium enhancement. Inconclusive indicates inconclusive or not applicable for endomyocardial biopsy."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig3.jpeg" height="2286" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Proposed diagnostic algorithm for patients with CA. CMR = cardiac MRI, ECV = extracellular volume, H:CL = heart-to–contralateral chest ratio, LGE = late gadolinium enhancement. <i>Inconclusive</i> indicates inconclusive or not applicable for endomyocardial biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic" aria-label="Typical morphologic findings of CA. Four-chamber (a) and short-axis (b) views on conventional transthoracic echocardiograms reveal typical morphologic findings of CA, with concentric thickening of the walls of the nondilated LV and thickening of the right ventricle (RV). The thickened intraventricular septum wall exhibits increased echogenicity, with a speckled appearance (arrows in a) on the four-chamber view."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig4a.jpeg" height="1488" width="1476" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Typical morphologic findings of CA. Four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and short-axis <b>(b)</b> views on conventional transthoracic echocardiograms reveal typical morphologic findings of CA, with concentric thickening of the walls of the nondilated LV and thickening of the right ventricle (RV). The thickened intraventricular septum wall exhibits increased echogenicity, with a speckled appearance (arrows in <b>a</b>) on the four-chamber view.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic" aria-label="Typical morphologic findings of CA. Four-chamber (a) and short-axis (b) views on conventional transthoracic echocardiograms reveal typical morphologic findings of CA, with concentric thickening of the walls of the nondilated LV and thickening of the right ventricle (RV). The thickened intraventricular septum wall exhibits increased echogenicity, with a speckled appearance (arrows in a) on the four-chamber view."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig4b.jpeg" height="1488" width="1473" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Typical morphologic findings of CA. Four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and short-axis <b>(b)</b> views on conventional transthoracic echocardiograms reveal typical morphologic findings of CA, with concentric thickening of the walls of the nondilated LV and thickening of the right ventricle (RV). The thickened intraventricular septum wall exhibits increased echogenicity, with a speckled appearance (arrows in <b>a</b>) on the four-chamber view.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic" aria-label="Myocardial strain analysis based on speckle-tracking echocardiography reveals impaired global longitudinal strain in a patient with CA. Top: Diagram depicts polar map of peak systolic (Syst.) longitudinal strain. EDV = end-diastolic volume, EF = ejection fraction, Endo = endocardial, EndoGLS= global longitudinal strain in the endocardial layer, ESV = end-systolic volume, SD-LS-Syst. = standard deviation of global longitudinal strain. Bottom: Graph depicts impaired longitudinal strain in the basal segments relative to the apical segments (ie, apical-sparing pattern). Vertical axis data are longitudinal strain percentages. Horizontal axis data are times, in milliseconds."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig5.jpeg" height="2425" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Myocardial strain analysis based on speckle-tracking echocardiography reveals impaired global longitudinal strain in a patient with CA. Top: Diagram depicts polar map of peak systolic <i>(Syst.)</i> longitudinal strain. <i>EDV</i> = end-diastolic volume, <i>EF</i> = ejection fraction, <i>Endo</i> = endocardial, <i>EndoGLS</i> = global longitudinal strain in the endocardial layer, <i>ESV</i> = end-systolic volume, <i>SD-LS-Syst.</i> = standard deviation of global longitudinal strain. Bottom: Graph depicts impaired longitudinal strain in the basal segments relative to the apical segments (ie, apical-sparing pattern). Vertical axis data are longitudinal strain percentages. Horizontal axis data are times, in milliseconds.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic" aria-label="LV remodeling phenotypes in three patients with CA. For each pattern, representative paired LV images in a three-chamber LV outflow tract view (left) and mid-LV short-axis view (right) are presented. (a) Cine cardiac MR images show symmetric thickening, which traditionally has been considered a characteristic pattern. (b) Cine cardiac MR images show asymmetric thickening, which was recently proven to be highly prevalent in CA. (c) Cine cardiac MR images sho no thickening, which is a less common but recognizable finding."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig6a.jpeg" height="1192" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. LV remodeling phenotypes in three patients with CA. For each pattern, representative paired LV images in a three-chamber LV outflow tract view (left) and mid-LV short-axis view (right) are presented. <b>(a)</b> Cine cardiac MR images show symmetric thickening, which traditionally has been considered a characteristic pattern. <b>(b)</b> Cine cardiac MR images show asymmetric thickening, which was recently proven to be highly prevalent in CA. <b>(c)</b> Cine cardiac MR images show no thickening, which is a less common but recognizable finding.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic" aria-label="LV remodeling phenotypes in three patients with CA. For each pattern, representative paired LV images in a three-chamber LV outflow tract view (left) and mid-LV short-axis view (right) are presented. (a) Cine cardiac MR images show symmetric thickening, which traditionally has been considered a characteristic pattern. (b) Cine cardiac MR images show asymmetric thickening, which was recently proven to be highly prevalent in CA. (c) Cine cardiac MR images sho no thickening, which is a less common but recognizable finding."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig6b.jpeg" height="1194" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. LV remodeling phenotypes in three patients with CA. For each pattern, representative paired LV images in a three-chamber LV outflow tract view (left) and mid-LV short-axis view (right) are presented. <b>(a)</b> Cine cardiac MR images show symmetric thickening, which traditionally has been considered a characteristic pattern. <b>(b)</b> Cine cardiac MR images show asymmetric thickening, which was recently proven to be highly prevalent in CA. <b>(c)</b> Cine cardiac MR images show no thickening, which is a less common but recognizable finding.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic" aria-label="LV remodeling phenotypes in three patients with CA. For each pattern, representative paired LV images in a three-chamber LV outflow tract view (left) and mid-LV short-axis view (right) are presented. (a) Cine cardiac MR images show symmetric thickening, which traditionally has been considered a characteristic pattern. (b) Cine cardiac MR images show asymmetric thickening, which was recently proven to be highly prevalent in CA. (c) Cine cardiac MR images sho no thickening, which is a less common but recognizable finding."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig6c.jpeg" height="1193" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. LV remodeling phenotypes in three patients with CA. For each pattern, representative paired LV images in a three-chamber LV outflow tract view (left) and mid-LV short-axis view (right) are presented. <b>(a)</b> Cine cardiac MR images show symmetric thickening, which traditionally has been considered a characteristic pattern. <b>(b)</b> Cine cardiac MR images show asymmetric thickening, which was recently proven to be highly prevalent in CA. <b>(c)</b> Cine cardiac MR images show no thickening, which is a less common but recognizable finding.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic" aria-label="ATTRm in a 60-year-old woman. Mid-LV short-axis view (a) and three-chamber LV outflow tract view (b) LGE MR images show global LV subendocardial LGE (arrows) and a dark blood pool, which are characteristic of CA. RV and LV atrial LGE (arrowheads) also is evident."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig7a.jpeg" height="1198" width="1240" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. ATTR<sub>m</sub> in a 60-year-old woman. Mid-LV short-axis view <b>(a)</b> and three-chamber LV outflow tract view <b>(b)</b> LGE MR images show global LV subendocardial LGE (arrows) and a dark blood pool, which are characteristic of CA. RV and LV atrial LGE (arrowheads) also is evident.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic" aria-label="ATTRm in a 60-year-old woman. Mid-LV short-axis view (a) and three-chamber LV outflow tract view (b) LGE MR images show global LV subendocardial LGE (arrows) and a dark blood pool, which are characteristic of CA. RV and LV atrial LGE (arrowheads) also is evident."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig7b.jpeg" height="1198" width="1209" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. ATTR<sub>m</sub> in a 60-year-old woman. Mid-LV short-axis view <b>(a)</b> and three-chamber LV outflow tract view <b>(b)</b> LGE MR images show global LV subendocardial LGE (arrows) and a dark blood pool, which are characteristic of CA. RV and LV atrial LGE (arrowheads) also is evident.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic" aria-label="Variable (ie, atypical) LGE pattern in four patients with CA. Mid-LV short-axis view LGE MR images depict a focal patchy LGE pattern (arrow) (a), diffuse patchy LGE pattern (arrows) (b), subepicardial LGE pattern (arrow) (c), and diffuse transmural LGE pattern (arrows) (d)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig8a.jpeg" height="1148" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Variable (ie, atypical) LGE pattern in four patients with CA. Mid-LV short-axis view LGE MR images depict a focal patchy LGE pattern (arrow) <b>(a)</b>, diffuse patchy LGE pattern (arrows) <b>(b)</b>, subepicardial LGE pattern (arrow) <b>(c)</b>, and diffuse transmural LGE pattern (arrows) <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic" aria-label="Variable (ie, atypical) LGE pattern in four patients with CA. Mid-LV short-axis view LGE MR images depict a focal patchy LGE pattern (arrow) (a), diffuse patchy LGE pattern (arrows) (b), subepicardial LGE pattern (arrow) (c), and diffuse transmural LGE pattern (arrows) (d)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig8b.jpeg" height="1118" width="1165" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Variable (ie, atypical) LGE pattern in four patients with CA. Mid-LV short-axis view LGE MR images depict a focal patchy LGE pattern (arrow) <b>(a)</b>, diffuse patchy LGE pattern (arrows) <b>(b)</b>, subepicardial LGE pattern (arrow) <b>(c)</b>, and diffuse transmural LGE pattern (arrows) <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic" aria-label="Variable (ie, atypical) LGE pattern in four patients with CA. Mid-LV short-axis view LGE MR images depict a focal patchy LGE pattern (arrow) (a), diffuse patchy LGE pattern (arrows) (b), subepicardial LGE pattern (arrow) (c), and diffuse transmural LGE pattern (arrows) (d)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig8c.jpeg" height="1118" width="1166" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. Variable (ie, atypical) LGE pattern in four patients with CA. Mid-LV short-axis view LGE MR images depict a focal patchy LGE pattern (arrow) <b>(a)</b>, diffuse patchy LGE pattern (arrows) <b>(b)</b>, subepicardial LGE pattern (arrow) <b>(c)</b>, and diffuse transmural LGE pattern (arrows) <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic" aria-label="Variable (ie, atypical) LGE pattern in four patients with CA. Mid-LV short-axis view LGE MR images depict a focal patchy LGE pattern (arrow) (a), diffuse patchy LGE pattern (arrows) (b), subepicardial LGE pattern (arrow) (c), and diffuse transmural LGE pattern (arrows) (d)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig8d.jpeg" height="1118" width="1170" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span>. Variable (ie, atypical) LGE pattern in four patients with CA. Mid-LV short-axis view LGE MR images depict a focal patchy LGE pattern (arrow) <b>(a)</b>, diffuse patchy LGE pattern (arrows) <b>(b)</b>, subepicardial LGE pattern (arrow) <b>(c)</b>, and diffuse transmural LGE pattern (arrows) <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic" aria-label="Apparent progression of CA over time. Mid-LV short-axis LGE MR images show amyloid accumulation in CA, progressing from no evidence of LGE (left image) to the appearance of subendocardial LGE (arrows in middle image), which is the typical pattern, and culminating in the progression to transmural LGE (arrows in right image)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig9.jpeg" height="1666" width="3600" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Apparent progression of CA over time. Mid-LV short-axis LGE MR images show amyloid accumulation in CA, progressing from no evidence of LGE (left image) to the appearance of subendocardial LGE (arrows in middle image), which is the typical pattern, and culminating in the progression to transmural LGE (arrows in right image).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic" aria-label="Base-to-apex gradient impairment pattern in a 76-year-old man with CA. LGE MR image (three-chamber LV outflow tract view) shows increased late enhancement at the base relative to the apex of the myocardium, highlighting the base-to-apex gradient (arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig10.jpeg" height="1301" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Base-to-apex gradient impairment pattern in a 76-year-old man with CA. LGE MR image (three-chamber LV outflow tract view) shows increased late enhancement at the base relative to the apex of the myocardium, highlighting the base-to-apex gradient (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic" aria-label="Examples of inversion-time scout assessment in a patient with hypertensive heart disease (top) and a patient with CA (bottom). Each set of images was acquired during a single breath hold, 7 minutes after administration of gadolinium-based contrast material. In the patient with hypertensive heart disease, the blood pool reached the null point (ie, became black) (red square) before the myocardium (blue square) did. This is the normal pattern observed during inversion-time scout assessment. Conversely, in the patient with CA, the entire myocardium crossed the null point (blue square) before the blood pool (red square) did, indicating diffuse global T1 shortening."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig11.jpeg" height="1528" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Examples of inversion-time scout assessment in a patient with hypertensive heart disease (top) and a patient with CA (bottom). Each set of images was acquired during a single breath hold, 7 minutes after administration of gadolinium-based contrast material. In the patient with hypertensive heart disease, the blood pool reached the null point (ie, became black) (red square) before the myocardium (blue square) did. This is the normal pattern observed during inversion-time scout assessment. Conversely, in the patient with CA, the entire myocardium crossed the null point (blue square) before the blood pool (red square) did, indicating diffuse global T1 shortening.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic" aria-label="Pitfalls of LGE MRI in a patient with CA. LGE MR images of the middle LV short-axis view obtained with inappropriate (160-msec) (a) and appropriate (280-msec) (b) inversion-time settings. The inappropriate inversion-time setting resulted in a mirror image of the true pattern."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig12a.jpeg" height="1234" width="1321" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Pitfalls of LGE MRI in a patient with CA. LGE MR images of the middle LV short-axis view obtained with inappropriate (160-msec) <b>(a)</b> and appropriate (280-msec) <b>(b)</b> inversion-time settings. The inappropriate inversion-time setting resulted in a mirror image of the true pattern.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic" aria-label="Pitfalls of LGE MRI in a patient with CA. LGE MR images of the middle LV short-axis view obtained with inappropriate (160-msec) (a) and appropriate (280-msec) (b) inversion-time settings. The inappropriate inversion-time setting resulted in a mirror image of the true pattern."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig12b.jpeg" height="1234" width="1327" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Pitfalls of LGE MRI in a patient with CA. LGE MR images of the middle LV short-axis view obtained with inappropriate (160-msec) <b>(a)</b> and appropriate (280-msec) <b>(b)</b> inversion-time settings. The inappropriate inversion-time setting resulted in a mirror image of the true pattern.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic" aria-label="Native T1 and ECV maps in the mid-LV short-axis view in a 55-year-old man with LV thickening caused by CA (a) and a 46-year-old man with noncardiac amyloidosis–related heart failure (b). The man with CA (a) exhibited significantly elevated mean native T1 (1562 msec) and ECV (63%) values relative to those in the man with noncardiac amyloidosis–related heart failure (1291 msec and 27%, respectively) (b)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig13a.jpeg" height="1143" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Native T1 and ECV maps in the mid-LV short-axis view in a 55-year-old man with LV thickening caused by CA <b>(a)</b> and a 46-year-old man with noncardiac amyloidosis–related heart failure <b>(b)</b>. The man with CA <b>(a)</b> exhibited significantly elevated mean native T1 (1562 msec) and ECV (63%) values relative to those in the man with noncardiac amyloidosis–related heart failure (1291 msec and 27%, respectively) <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic" aria-label="Native T1 and ECV maps in the mid-LV short-axis view in a 55-year-old man with LV thickening caused by CA (a) and a 46-year-old man with noncardiac amyloidosis–related heart failure (b). The man with CA (a) exhibited significantly elevated mean native T1 (1562 msec) and ECV (63%) values relative to those in the man with noncardiac amyloidosis–related heart failure (1291 msec and 27%, respectively) (b)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig13b.jpeg" height="1146" width="2499" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Native T1 and ECV maps in the mid-LV short-axis view in a 55-year-old man with LV thickening caused by CA <b>(a)</b> and a 46-year-old man with noncardiac amyloidosis–related heart failure <b>(b)</b>. The man with CA <b>(a)</b> exhibited significantly elevated mean native T1 (1562 msec) and ECV (63%) values relative to those in the man with noncardiac amyloidosis–related heart failure (1291 msec and 27%, respectively) <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic" aria-label="Myocardial T2 maps of the mid-LV short-axis view in a 69-year-old woman with LV thickening (arrow) caused by AL (a), a 73-year-old man with LV thickening caused by ATTR (b), and a 61-year-old man with noncardiac amyloidosis (Non-CA) (c). Myocardial T2 values were significantly increased in the patient with AL (78 msec in the septum) (a) relative to those in the patient with ATTR (52 msec) (b) and the patient with noncardiac amyloidosis (45 msec) (c)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig14a.jpeg" height="1176" width="1238" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Myocardial T2 maps of the mid-LV short-axis view in a 69-year-old woman with LV thickening (arrow) caused by AL <b>(a)</b>, a 73-year-old man with LV thickening caused by ATTR <b>(b)</b>, and a 61-year-old man with noncardiac amyloidosis <i>(Non-CA)</i> <b>(c)</b>. Myocardial T2 values were significantly increased in the patient with AL (78 msec in the septum) <b>(a)</b> relative to those in the patient with ATTR (52 msec) <b>(b)</b> and the patient with noncardiac amyloidosis (45 msec) <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic" aria-label="Myocardial T2 maps of the mid-LV short-axis view in a 69-year-old woman with LV thickening (arrow) caused by AL (a), a 73-year-old man with LV thickening caused by ATTR (b), and a 61-year-old man with noncardiac amyloidosis (Non-CA) (c). Myocardial T2 values were significantly increased in the patient with AL (78 msec in the septum) (a) relative to those in the patient with ATTR (52 msec) (b) and the patient with noncardiac amyloidosis (45 msec) (c)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig14b.jpeg" height="1176" width="1236" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Myocardial T2 maps of the mid-LV short-axis view in a 69-year-old woman with LV thickening (arrow) caused by AL <b>(a)</b>, a 73-year-old man with LV thickening caused by ATTR <b>(b)</b>, and a 61-year-old man with noncardiac amyloidosis <i>(Non-CA)</i> <b>(c)</b>. Myocardial T2 values were significantly increased in the patient with AL (78 msec in the septum) <b>(a)</b> relative to those in the patient with ATTR (52 msec) <b>(b)</b> and the patient with noncardiac amyloidosis (45 msec) <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic" aria-label="Myocardial T2 maps of the mid-LV short-axis view in a 69-year-old woman with LV thickening (arrow) caused by AL (a), a 73-year-old man with LV thickening caused by ATTR (b), and a 61-year-old man with noncardiac amyloidosis (Non-CA) (c). Myocardial T2 values were significantly increased in the patient with AL (78 msec in the septum) (a) relative to those in the patient with ATTR (52 msec) (b) and the patient with noncardiac amyloidosis (45 msec) (c)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig14c.jpeg" height="1176" width="1234" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span>. Myocardial T2 maps of the mid-LV short-axis view in a 69-year-old woman with LV thickening (arrow) caused by AL <b>(a)</b>, a 73-year-old man with LV thickening caused by ATTR <b>(b)</b>, and a 61-year-old man with noncardiac amyloidosis <i>(Non-CA)</i> <b>(c)</b>. Myocardial T2 values were significantly increased in the patient with AL (78 msec in the septum) <b>(a)</b> relative to those in the patient with ATTR (52 msec) <b>(b)</b> and the patient with noncardiac amyloidosis (45 msec) <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic" aria-label="Cardiac MRI–based myocardial strain imaging in CA, with circumferential strain time curves for the lateral, posterior, anterior, and septal LV segments (left) and a superimposed color-coded strain map (right) in the LV short-axis plane. Strain analysis reveals a nonuniform reduction in the negative peak of circumferential strain. The peak circumferential strain time was delayed and variable."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig15.jpeg" height="1340" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Cardiac MRI–based myocardial strain imaging in CA, with circumferential strain time curves for the lateral, posterior, anterior, and septal LV segments (left) and a superimposed color-coded strain map (right) in the LV short-axis plane. Strain analysis reveals a nonuniform reduction in the negative peak of circumferential strain. The peak circumferential strain time was delayed and variable.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic" aria-label="Anterior planar 99m Tc-PYP bone scintigrams (left) and coronal (middle) and axial (right) fused SPECT/CT images in an 80-year-old man with ATTR (a) and an 81-year-old woman with AL (b). ATTR is characterized by high myocardial uptake of radiotracer, whereas no significant myocardial uptake is seen in the patient with AL."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig16a.jpeg" height="1135" width="3400" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Anterior planar <sup>99m</sup>Tc-PYP bone scintigrams (left) and coronal (middle) and axial (right) fused SPECT/CT images in an 80-year-old man with ATTR <b>(a)</b> and an 81-year-old woman with AL <b>(b)</b>. ATTR is characterized by high myocardial uptake of radiotracer, whereas no significant myocardial uptake is seen in the patient with AL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic" aria-label="Anterior planar 99m Tc-PYP bone scintigrams (left) and coronal (middle) and axial (right) fused SPECT/CT images in an 80-year-old man with ATTR (a) and an 81-year-old woman with AL (b). ATTR is characterized by high myocardial uptake of radiotracer, whereas no significant myocardial uptake is seen in the patient with AL."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig16b.jpeg" height="1130" width="3400" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Anterior planar <sup>99m</sup>Tc-PYP bone scintigrams (left) and coronal (middle) and axial (right) fused SPECT/CT images in an 80-year-old man with ATTR <b>(a)</b> and an 81-year-old woman with AL <b>(b)</b>. ATTR is characterized by high myocardial uptake of radiotracer, whereas no significant myocardial uptake is seen in the patient with AL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic" aria-label="123 I-MIBG scintigraphy in a 78-year-old man with CA. Anterior-view late 123 I-MIBG image shows severely reduced radiotracer uptake in the heart (heart-to-mediastinum uptake ratio [H/M], 1.35), suggesting a poor prognosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig17.jpeg" height="1416" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span>. <sup>123</sup>I-MIBG scintigraphy in a 78-year-old man with CA. Anterior-view late <sup>123</sup>I-MIBG image shows severely reduced radiotracer uptake in the heart (heart-to-mediastinum uptake ratio <i>[H/M],</i> 1.35), suggesting a poor prognosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic" aria-label="Cardiac CT with LIE and ECV imaging in a 63-year-old man with chronic heart failure. Cardiac MRI was not performed because the patient had an implanted pacemaker. Low-energy VMI at 50 keV (a, b), iodine density imaging (c), and CT-ECV imaging (d) were performed by using dual-energy CT. (a–c) The CT-LIE images revealed global subendocardial LIE, RV LIE, and a dark blood pool, which are clearly visualized with 50-keV VMI (a, b) and iodine density imaging (c). (d) The myocardial ECV was markedly elevated (mean ECV, 69%). The patient was diagnosed with ATTR."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig18a.jpeg" height="1193" width="1323" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. Cardiac CT with LIE and ECV imaging in a 63-year-old man with chronic heart failure. Cardiac MRI was not performed because the patient had an implanted pacemaker. Low-energy VMI at 50 keV <b>(a, b)</b>, iodine density imaging <b>(c)</b>, and CT-ECV imaging <b>(d)</b> were performed by using dual-energy CT. <b>(a–c)</b> The CT-LIE images revealed global subendocardial LIE, RV LIE, and a dark blood pool, which are clearly visualized with 50-keV VMI <b>(a, b)</b> and iodine density imaging <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d)</b> The myocardial ECV was markedly elevated (mean ECV, 69%). The patient was diagnosed with ATTR.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic" aria-label="Cardiac CT with LIE and ECV imaging in a 63-year-old man with chronic heart failure. Cardiac MRI was not performed because the patient had an implanted pacemaker. Low-energy VMI at 50 keV (a, b), iodine density imaging (c), and CT-ECV imaging (d) were performed by using dual-energy CT. (a–c) The CT-LIE images revealed global subendocardial LIE, RV LIE, and a dark blood pool, which are clearly visualized with 50-keV VMI (a, b) and iodine density imaging (c). (d) The myocardial ECV was markedly elevated (mean ECV, 69%). The patient was diagnosed with ATTR."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig18b.jpeg" height="1193" width="1324" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. Cardiac CT with LIE and ECV imaging in a 63-year-old man with chronic heart failure. Cardiac MRI was not performed because the patient had an implanted pacemaker. Low-energy VMI at 50 keV <b>(a, b)</b>, iodine density imaging <b>(c)</b>, and CT-ECV imaging <b>(d)</b> were performed by using dual-energy CT. <b>(a–c)</b> The CT-LIE images revealed global subendocardial LIE, RV LIE, and a dark blood pool, which are clearly visualized with 50-keV VMI <b>(a, b)</b> and iodine density imaging <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d)</b> The myocardial ECV was markedly elevated (mean ECV, 69%). The patient was diagnosed with ATTR.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18c" class="graphic" aria-label="Cardiac CT with LIE and ECV imaging in a 63-year-old man with chronic heart failure. Cardiac MRI was not performed because the patient had an implanted pacemaker. Low-energy VMI at 50 keV (a, b), iodine density imaging (c), and CT-ECV imaging (d) were performed by using dual-energy CT. (a–c) The CT-LIE images revealed global subendocardial LIE, RV LIE, and a dark blood pool, which are clearly visualized with 50-keV VMI (a, b) and iodine density imaging (c). (d) The myocardial ECV was markedly elevated (mean ECV, 69%). The patient was diagnosed with ATTR."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig18c.jpeg" height="1262" width="1323" aria-labelledby="fig18c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18c</span>. Cardiac CT with LIE and ECV imaging in a 63-year-old man with chronic heart failure. Cardiac MRI was not performed because the patient had an implanted pacemaker. Low-energy VMI at 50 keV <b>(a, b)</b>, iodine density imaging <b>(c)</b>, and CT-ECV imaging <b>(d)</b> were performed by using dual-energy CT. <b>(a–c)</b> The CT-LIE images revealed global subendocardial LIE, RV LIE, and a dark blood pool, which are clearly visualized with 50-keV VMI <b>(a, b)</b> and iodine density imaging <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d)</b> The myocardial ECV was markedly elevated (mean ECV, 69%). The patient was diagnosed with ATTR.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig18c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18d" class="graphic" aria-label="Cardiac CT with LIE and ECV imaging in a 63-year-old man with chronic heart failure. Cardiac MRI was not performed because the patient had an implanted pacemaker. Low-energy VMI at 50 keV (a, b), iodine density imaging (c), and CT-ECV imaging (d) were performed by using dual-energy CT. (a–c) The CT-LIE images revealed global subendocardial LIE, RV LIE, and a dark blood pool, which are clearly visualized with 50-keV VMI (a, b) and iodine density imaging (c). (d) The myocardial ECV was markedly elevated (mean ECV, 69%). The patient was diagnosed with ATTR."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig18d.jpeg" height="1258" width="1326" aria-labelledby="fig18d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18d</span>. Cardiac CT with LIE and ECV imaging in a 63-year-old man with chronic heart failure. Cardiac MRI was not performed because the patient had an implanted pacemaker. Low-energy VMI at 50 keV <b>(a, b)</b>, iodine density imaging <b>(c)</b>, and CT-ECV imaging <b>(d)</b> were performed by using dual-energy CT. <b>(a–c)</b> The CT-LIE images revealed global subendocardial LIE, RV LIE, and a dark blood pool, which are clearly visualized with 50-keV VMI <b>(a, b)</b> and iodine density imaging <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d)</b> The myocardial ECV was markedly elevated (mean ECV, 69%). The patient was diagnosed with ATTR.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig18d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic" aria-label="Transcatheter aortic valve replacement in an 82-year-old patient with occult CA and aortic stenosis. (a) Transcatheter aortic valve replacement–planning CT images (in aortic valve plane and access routes) show anatomic suitability for the transcatheter aortic valve replacement procedure. (b) Mid-LV short-axis view CT-LIE image shows global subendocardial LIE. (c) Mid-LV short-axis view CT-ECV image shows markedly elevated myocardial ECV (mean ECV, 64%). Red indicates regions with high ECV, and green indicates regions with low ECV. (d) Anterior planar view 99m Tc-PYP bone scintigram reveals high myocardial uptake."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig19a.jpeg" height="1075" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Transcatheter aortic valve replacement in an 82-year-old patient with occult CA and aortic stenosis. <b>(a)</b> Transcatheter aortic valve replacement–planning CT images (in aortic valve plane and access routes) show anatomic suitability for the transcatheter aortic valve replacement procedure. <b>(b)</b> Mid-LV short-axis view CT-LIE image shows global subendocardial LIE. <b>(c)</b> Mid-LV short-axis view CT-ECV image shows markedly elevated myocardial ECV (mean ECV, 64%). Red indicates regions with high ECV, and green indicates regions with low ECV. <b>(d)</b> Anterior planar view <sup>99m</sup>Tc-PYP bone scintigram reveals high myocardial uptake.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190069&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic" aria-label="Transcatheter aortic valve replacement in an 82-year-old patient with occult CA and aortic stenosis. (a) Transcatheter aortic valve replacement–planning CT images (in aortic valve plane and access routes) show anatomic suitability for the transcatheter aortic valve replacement procedure. (b) Mid-LV short-axis view CT-LIE image shows global subendocardial LIE. (c) Mid-LV short-axis view CT-ECV image shows markedly elevated myocardial ECV (mean ECV, 64%). Red indicates regions with high ECV, and green indicates regions with low ECV. (d) Anterior planar view 99m Tc-PYP bone scintigram reveals high myocardial uptake."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190069/asset/images/large/rg.2020190069.fig19b.jpeg" height="1199" width="1236" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Transcatheter aortic valve replacement in an 82-year-old patient with occult CA and aortic stenosis. <b>(a)</b> Transcatheter aortic valve replacement–planning CT images (in aortic valve plane and access routes) show anatomic suitability for the transcatheter aortic valve replacement procedure. <b>(b)</b> Mid-LV short-axis view CT-LIE image shows global subendocardial LIE.